        <title>Fonts and Graphics</title>
        <dc:creator><![CDATA[@mod_taharok Taharok]]></dc:creator>
        <description><![CDATA[
          <p><a href="https://forum.moparisthebest.com/u/mod_taharok">@mod_taharok</a> wrote:</p>
          <blockquote>
              <p><a href="http://java.sun.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/awt/Font.html#Font(java.lang.String,%20int,%20int)" data-bbcode="true" rel="nofollow noopener">new Font(String, int, int)</a> should help you. You can specify which font you are using, the point of the font, and the style. As for color, it depends on what you are specifically doing. If you are using a Graphics object to draw things, then you can change the color using <a href="http://java.sun.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/awt/Graphics.html#setColor(java.awt.Color)" data-bbcode="true" rel="nofollow noopener">Graphics.setColor(Color)</a>. Or, if you are using AWT or Swing components to draw whatever it is you’re drawing, you can use <a href="http://java.sun.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/awt/Component.html#setForeground(java.awt.Color)" data-bbcode="true" rel="nofollow noopener">Component.setForeground(Color)</a> and <a href="http://java.sun.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/awt/Component.html#setBackground(java.awt.Color)" data-bbcode="true" rel="nofollow noopener">Component.setBackground(Color)</a> to change the colors of the component’s foreground (text and sometimes unactivated colors) and background (literal background in plain components), respectively.</p>
          </blockquote>
          <p><a href="https://forum.moparisthebest.com/t/fonts-and-graphics/314784/2">Read full topic</a></p>
        ]]></description>
